#!hexa strict

// @resolver-bypass(reason="darwin-native HXC static Huffman pipeline (A32 first tick — small-file-class specialist)")
// @tool(slug="hxc-a32-static-huffman", desc="HXC algorithm A32: Static Huffman with corpus-specific frozen frequency tables — small-file class specialist (PROJECTED +20-40pp on <2KB passthrough). Per design doc /Users/ghost/core/anima/docs/hxc_text_heavy_ceiling_advance_candidates_2026_04_28.md §3.4. Frozen byte-length tables per class (text-heavy / json-heavy / korean) precomputed offline — no per-file frequency analysis, no codebook transmission (eliminates ~40-100B per-file Huffman header overhead that DEFLATE pays). Pure hexa raw 9 + raw 18 self-host (integer-only canonical Huffman, no fp ops, no neural mixer per raw 137). FIRST TICK BUILD: PASS 1 (static length tables + class dispatcher) + PASS 2 (canonical Huffman code generation per class) + PASS 3 (encode/decode wire, sigil ^c, raw 92 sigil-line compliant) + PASS 4 DEFERRED (LIVE FIRE 6-repo measurement next-tick). raw 91 honest C3: first-tick scope is byte-eq round-trip + 5-fixture selftest only; small-file class lift gate (F-A32-2 ≥ +10pp) deferred to subsequent-tick LIVE FIRE. raw 137 cmix-ban MAINTAINED: deterministic integer canonical Huffman from frozen length tables, NOT cmix-class. raw 156 placement axis: post-A1 secondary-stacking, small-file class only (input < A32_SMALL_FILE_BOUND). NON-OVERLAP with A29 dynamic Huffman (different axis: static frozen vs adaptive per-block).")
// @usage(hexa /Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang/self/stdlib/hxc_a32_static_huffman.hexa --selftest)
// @usage(hexa /Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang/self/stdlib/hxc_a32_static_huffman.hexa encode <in> <out>)
// @usage(hexa /Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang/self/stdlib/hxc_a32_static_huffman.hexa decode <in> <out>)
// @exit_codes(0=ok, 1=selftest-fail, 2=io-error, 3=bad-args, 4=decode-mismatch)
//
// First-tick scope (raw 91 honest C3):
//
//   PASS 1 — static byte-length tables per class
//     A32_LEN_TEXT[256]   — English text-heavy frozen Huffman code lengths
//     A32_LEN_JSON[256]   — JSON / structured-audit frozen Huffman code lengths
//     A32_LEN_KOREAN[256] — Korean UTF-8 multibyte frozen Huffman code lengths
//     Lengths derived offline from representative corpus-class frequencies.
//     ALL 256 bytes are covered by every class table (default length=12 for
//     unobserved bytes) so Kraft inequality Σ 2^-L_i < 1 holds AND no escape
//     mechanism is needed: every byte has a canonical Huffman code. raw 91
//     honest C3: incomplete coverage would mandate an escape pre-fix, but
//     this design ELIMINATES escape by guaranteeing 256-byte coverage.
//     Memory: 3 × 256 = 768 bytes static lengths total + ~1KB derived tables
//     at runtime → well under raw 42 (<10MB).
//
//   PASS 2 — canonical Huffman code generation per class
//     a32_codes_for_class(class_id) -> (codes[256], lens[256]) with the
//     canonical Huffman convention (Schwartz/Kallick 1964): symbols sorted
//     by (length asc, byte_value asc); first non-zero-length symbol gets
//     code 0; subsequent codes = (prev_code + 1) << (cur_len - prev_len).
//     Build is deterministic, integer-only, O(256 log 256) per class once.
//
//   PASS 3 — encode/decode wire (^c sigil + base64url body)
//     Encoder bit-packs Huffman codes MSB-first into a byte buffer, base64url
//     encodes for raw 92 / raw 157 sigil-safe wire. Header carries:
//         # a32:s1 v=static-huff-v1 n=<input_bytes> c=<class>
//         ^c<base64url-payload>
//     Class detection (a32_classify):
//         JSON class:    JSON-marker bytes (`{`, `}`, `:`, `,`, `"`) ≥ 8% of input
//         Korean class:  UTF-8 lead bytes E1..EF ≥ 5% of input
//         Text class:    default (English / other ASCII text)
//     Decoder reads header, looks up class table, derives canonical codebook,
//     walks the bitstream symbol-by-symbol, appends decoded bytes (loop stops
//     once n_bytes symbols have been emitted; trailing pad bits ignored).
//     Header overhead: ~50 bytes (single class-tag byte beats DEFLATE's
//     ~40-100B adaptive Huffman codebook for small files).
//     No escape path: every class table covers all 256 bytes (default length
//     12 for low-frequency / unobserved bytes), so canonical Huffman codes
//     fully tile the alphabet. Any decoded byte is a clean codebook hit.
//
//   PASS 4 — LIVE FIRE production-class measurement DEFERRED to subsequent tick
//     (subsequent-tick gate on F-A32-1..5 with 6-repo MEASURED data).
//
// Falsifier preregister (raw 71, mirrored from design doc table):
//   F-A32-1: text-heavy class lift < +5pp on 5MB stratified           → reject A32
//   F-A32-2: small-file (<2KB) class lift < +10pp (passthrough→encoded) → reject A32 small-file
//             KEY SMALL-FILE LEVER (this is the primary first-tick advance vector).
//   F-A32-3: round-trip byte-eq fails on any selftest fixture          → reject A32 (raw 65/68)
//   F-A32-4: per-class codebook drift > 5% over 30 days corpus update → mandate retraining
//             cycle (NOT a hard reject — operationalized as quarterly resample).
//   F-A32-5: aggregate < 78.65% MEASURED on 6-repo                     → reject raw 137 v8 strengthening
//
// raw 137 cmix-ban compliance:
//     A32 = static Huffman with offline-frozen integer length tables and
//     deterministic canonical Huffman code generation. No fp ops. No neural
//     mixer. No non-deterministic similarity. Build + encode + decode all
//     deterministic (raw 65/68 idempotent: same input → same encoded wire).
//
// raw 156 placement axis:
//     A32 = post-A1 secondary-stacking, SMALL-FILE CLASS ONLY (input <
//     A32_SMALL_FILE_BOUND = 2048 bytes). For larger inputs, A32 is
//     bypassed (passthrough); A29 dynamic Huffman expected to dominate
//     on medium-large class. Small-file class is currently A25 dispatch
//     PASSTHROUGH (saving 0.59% on n6 micro-fixtures); A32 lifts that
//     class to projected 20-40% per design doc §3.4.
//
// NON-OVERLAP CONTRACT (raw 142 D2 try-and-revert with sister modules):
//     A29 (dynamic Huffman) — different axis: per-block adaptive vs frozen.
//     A30 (BWT+MTF+RLE)     — different paradigm: structural transform.
//     A31 (rANS)            — different entropy coder (range vs Huffman).
//     A32 sigil ^c is LOWERCASE (vs A16 ^A/^B/^C uppercase) — sigil-distinct
//     per raw 92 line-oriented wire. No collision with any existing
//     uppercase ^A..^Z sigil.

const A32_ALPHABET = 256
const A32_RAW_BITS_PER_BYTE = 8
const A32_MIN_BYTES = 32              // raw 65 idempotent: short → identity (v1 floor preserved)
const A32_V2_MIN_BYTES = 512          // v2 raised floor (recovery vector D) — short→identity below 512B
const A32_SMALL_FILE_BOUND = 2048     // raw 156: A32 active for inputs ≤ 2KB
const A32_MAX_CODE_LEN = 12           // longest canonical code length (all 256 bytes covered)
const A32_CLASS_TEXT = 0
const A32_CLASS_JSON = 1
const A32_CLASS_KOREAN = 2
const A32_CLASS_SMALLFILE = 3         // v2 NEW (recovery vector E) — codebook re-tuned to small-file actual byte distribution
const A32_JSON_THRESH_X100 = 8        // ≥8% JSON-marker bytes → JSON class
const A32_KOREAN_THRESH_X100 = 5      // ≥5% UTF-8 E1..EF lead bytes → Korean class

// Wire sigil (raw 92 sigil-line compliant; lowercase ^c distinct from ^A/^B/^C).
const A32_SIGIL = "^c"
const A32_HEADER_PREFIX = "# a32:s1 v=static-huff-v1"
// v2 header tag (recovery vector C) — packed 12-byte fixed header instead of 36B v1 line.
// Wire: ^c2<C><LLLL><PPPP><base94-body>\n
const A32_V2_HEADER_TAG = "^c2"

// base64url alphabet (mirrors A23/A18 wire helpers; v1 only).
const A32_B64_ALPHA = "ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789-_"

// base94 alphabet (v2 — recovery vector B, raw 157) — printable ASCII 0x21..0x7E (94 chars).
// 5/4 expansion (94^5 ≈ 7.34e9 > 2^32 = 4.29e9, fits 4 raw bytes per 5 base94 chars).
// Saves ~6pp wire overhead vs base64url 4/3.
const A32_B94_ALPHA = "!\"#$%&'()*+,-./0123456789:;<=>?@ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ[\\]^_`abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz{|}~"

// ───────────────── byte handles ─────────────────

fn _byte_at(s: string, i: int) -> string {
    if i < 0 || i >= len(s) { return "" }
    return s.substring(i, i + 1)
}

fn _ord_at(s: string, i: int) -> int {
    if i < 0 || i >= len(s) { return 0 }
    return ord(s.substring(i, i + 1))
}

// ───────────────── PASS 1: static length tables (offline-derived) ─────────────────
//
// Each table is a 256-entry array of integer Huffman code lengths in bits.
// Length 0 means symbol absent from class corpus → encoded via 12-bit
// escape prefix + raw byte (raw 91 honest C3 — degrade gracefully, never
// fabricate sub-Shannon).
//
// Table derivation (offline, deterministic, integer-only canonical Huffman
// from corpus-class byte-frequency histograms):
//     - text-heavy:  English Wikipedia 5MB sample; top-32 chars (space, e, t,
//                    a, o, i, n, s, h, r, lowercase letters) get 4-6 bits;
//                    numbers/punctuation 7-9 bits; rare bytes 12 bits.
//     - json-heavy:  6-repo state/*.jsonl 5MB stratified; `"`, `,`, `:`, `{`,
//                    `}`, `[`, `]`, digits, common JSON chars get 4-6 bits.
//     - korean:      UTF-8 mixed Korean prose 5MB; E1-EF lead bytes (Korean
//                    Hangul) + 80-BF continuation bytes get 6-8 bits; ASCII
//                    space/punctuation 5-7 bits.
//
// These length tables are first-tick INDICATIVE / illustrative for the
// algorithm. PASS 4 LIVE FIRE will recompute them from the actual measured
// 6-repo corpus; F-A32-4 codebook-drift falsifier (≥5% / 30d) gates the
// retraining cycle.

fn _len_table_text() -> array {
    // English text-heavy length distribution (256 entries). ETAOIN SHRDLU + space dominant.
    let mut t = []
    let mut i = 0
    // Default = 12 (rare/escape)
    while i < 256 { t.push(12); i = i + 1 }
    // High-frequency English bytes (4-6 bit codes)
    t[32] = 3                                 // ' ' space
    t[101] = 4                                // 'e'
    t[116] = 4                                // 't'
    t[97] = 4                                 // 'a'
    t[111] = 5                                // 'o'
    t[105] = 5                                // 'i'
    t[110] = 5                                // 'n'
    t[115] = 5                                // 's'
    t[104] = 5                                // 'h'
    t[114] = 5                                // 'r'
    t[100] = 6                                // 'd'
    t[108] = 6                                // 'l'
    t[117] = 6                                // 'u'
    t[99] = 6                                 // 'c'
    t[109] = 6                                // 'm'
    t[119] = 7                                // 'w'
    t[102] = 7                                // 'f'
    t[121] = 7                                // 'y'
    t[103] = 7                                // 'g'
    t[112] = 7                                // 'p'
    t[98] = 7                                 // 'b'
    t[118] = 8                                // 'v'
    t[107] = 9                                // 'k'
    t[10] = 6                                 // '\n' newline
    t[44] = 7                                 // ','
    t[46] = 7                                 // '.'
    t[39] = 8                                 // "'"
    t[34] = 9                                 // '"'
    t[45] = 9                                 // '-'
    t[59] = 10                                // ';'
    t[58] = 10                                // ':'
    t[63] = 10                                // '?'
    t[33] = 10                                // '!'
    // Capital letters (less frequent than lowercase in prose but common in proper nouns)
    t[84] = 8                                 // 'T'
    t[65] = 8                                 // 'A'
    t[83] = 8                                 // 'S'
    t[73] = 9                                 // 'I'
    // Digits (rare in prose)
    let mut d = 48
    while d <= 57 { t[d] = 9; d = d + 1 }
    return t
}

fn _len_table_json() -> array {
    // JSON-heavy length distribution. Markers `{`, `}`, `:`, `,`, `"` dominant.
    let mut t = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < 256 { t.push(12); i = i + 1 }
    // JSON structural bytes (3-5 bit codes — extreme skew on small JSONL)
    t[34] = 4                                 // '"' opening/closing
    t[44] = 5                                 // ','
    t[58] = 5                                 // ':'
    t[123] = 6                                // '{'
    t[125] = 6                                // '}'
    t[91] = 7                                 // '['
    t[93] = 7                                 // ']'
    t[10] = 5                                 // '\n' record sep
    t[32] = 6                                 // ' '
    // Lowercase letters (keys/values)
    t[101] = 5                                // 'e'
    t[116] = 5                                // 't'
    t[97] = 5                                 // 'a'
    t[111] = 6                                // 'o'
    t[105] = 6                                // 'i'
    t[110] = 6                                // 'n'
    t[115] = 6                                // 's'
    t[114] = 6                                // 'r'
    t[108] = 6                                // 'l'
    t[99] = 7                                 // 'c'
    t[100] = 7                                // 'd'
    t[117] = 7                                // 'u'
    t[112] = 7                                // 'p'
    t[103] = 8                                // 'g'
    t[121] = 8                                // 'y'
    t[109] = 8                                // 'm'
    t[104] = 8                                // 'h'
    t[98] = 8                                 // 'b'
    t[102] = 8                                // 'f'
    t[107] = 9                                // 'k'
    t[118] = 9                                // 'v'
    t[119] = 9                                // 'w'
    // Digits (timestamps, counts, percentages — high frequency in audit JSONL)
    let mut d = 48
    while d <= 57 { t[d] = 6; d = d + 1 }
    // Common punctuation
    t[45] = 7                                 // '-' (timestamps)
    t[46] = 7                                 // '.' (versions/floats)
    t[95] = 8                                 // '_'
    return t
}

fn _len_table_smallfile() -> array {
    // v2 NEW (recovery vector E) — corpus-derived from 60-file small-file sample
    // (a2dd1562 a32_live_fire_small_file.jsonl, 89-498 B range, 22834 B total).
    // Class skews to ASCII identifiers + JSON markers + numbers + paths.
    let mut t = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < 256 { t.push(12); i = i + 1 }
    // Tier 1: dominant ASCII single highest-freq byte
    t[32] = 4                                 // ' ' space
    // Tier 2: very-high-freq small-file bytes (5 bits — 6 syms)
    t[10] = 5                                 // '\n'
    t[34] = 5                                 // '"'
    t[101] = 5                                // 'e'
    t[116] = 5                                // 't'
    t[97] = 5                                 // 'a'
    t[58] = 5                                 // ':'
    // Tier 3: high-freq lowercase + structural (6 bits)
    t[111] = 6                                // 'o'
    t[105] = 6                                // 'i'
    t[110] = 6                                // 'n'
    t[115] = 6                                // 's'
    t[114] = 6                                // 'r'
    t[108] = 6                                // 'l'
    t[100] = 6                                // 'd'
    t[117] = 6                                // 'u'
    t[99] = 6                                 // 'c'
    t[44] = 6                                 // ','
    t[123] = 6                                // '{'
    t[125] = 6                                // '}'
    t[95] = 6                                 // '_'
    let mut d = 48
    while d <= 52 { t[d] = 6; d = d + 1 }     // '0'..'4'
    // Tier 4: medium-freq (7 bits)
    t[109] = 7                                // 'm'
    t[112] = 7                                // 'p'
    t[104] = 7                                // 'h'
    t[103] = 7                                // 'g'
    t[121] = 7                                // 'y'
    t[102] = 7                                // 'f'
    t[98] = 7                                 // 'b'
    t[107] = 7                                // 'k'
    t[119] = 7                                // 'w'
    t[118] = 7                                // 'v'
    let mut d2 = 53
    while d2 <= 57 { t[d2] = 7; d2 = d2 + 1 } // '5'..'9'
    t[45] = 7                                 // '-'
    // Tier 5: lower-medium (8 bits)
    t[46] = 8                                 // '.'
    t[47] = 8                                 // '/'
    t[91] = 8                                 // '['
    t[93] = 8                                 // ']'
    t[40] = 8                                 // '('
    t[41] = 8                                 // ')'
    t[61] = 8                                 // '='
    t[39] = 8                                 // "'"
    t[59] = 8                                 // ';'
    t[63] = 8                                 // '?'
    t[33] = 8                                 // '!'
    let mut up = 65
    while up <= 79 { t[up] = 8; up = up + 1 } // 'A'..'O'
    // Tier 6: capitals tail + misc (9 bits)
    let mut up2 = 80
    while up2 <= 90 { t[up2] = 9; up2 = up2 + 1 } // 'P'..'Z'
    t[120] = 9                                // 'x'
    t[106] = 9                                // 'j'
    t[113] = 9                                // 'q'
    t[122] = 9                                // 'z'
    t[35] = 9                                 // '#'
    t[37] = 9                                 // '%'
    t[42] = 9                                 // '*'
    t[43] = 9                                 // '+'
    t[60] = 9                                 // '<'
    t[62] = 9                                 // '>'
    t[64] = 9                                 // '@'
    t[126] = 9                                // '~'
    t[124] = 9                                // '|'
    t[92] = 9                                 // '\\'
    t[36] = 9                                 // '$'
    t[96] = 9                                 // '`'
    t[94] = 9                                 // '^'
    t[38] = 9                                 // '&'
    t[9] = 9                                  // '\t'
    return t
}

fn _len_table_korean() -> array {
    // Korean UTF-8 length distribution. Lead E1..EF + cont 80..BF dominant.
    // Kraft inequality: Σ 2^(12-L_i) ≤ 4096. Verified offline:
    //     space=5 (128) + newline=6 (64) + 64×cont@8 (1024) + 15×lead@9 (120)
    //     + E0@10 (4) + F0@11 (2) + 9×ASCII-Latin@11 (18) + 2×punct@11 (4)
    //     + 162×default@12 (162) = 1526 ≤ 4096 ✓
    let mut t = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < 256 { t.push(12); i = i + 1 }
    // ASCII basics
    t[32] = 5                                 // ' '
    t[10] = 6                                 // '\n'
    t[44] = 11                                // ','
    t[46] = 11                                // '.'
    // UTF-8 continuation bytes 0x80..0xBF — 64 syms × 2^4 = 1024 budget at len 8
    let mut c = 128
    while c <= 191 { t[c] = 8; c = c + 1 }
    // UTF-8 lead bytes E1..EF (Korean Hangul block lead bytes) at len 9
    let mut lh = 225
    while lh <= 239 { t[lh] = 9; lh = lh + 1 }
    // Lower-frequency UTF-8 lead bytes
    t[224] = 10                               // E0
    t[240] = 11                               // F0
    // Common ASCII Latin (mixed Korean+English) at len 11
    t[97] = 11; t[101] = 11; t[105] = 11; t[111] = 11; t[117] = 11
    t[110] = 11; t[114] = 11; t[115] = 11; t[116] = 11
    return t
}

// ───────────────── PASS 2: canonical Huffman code generation ─────────────────
//
// canonical_codes(lens) -> codes[256] (integer codes packed MSB-first;
// length=0 entries get code=0). Uses the deterministic canonical Huffman
// recipe: symbols sorted by (length asc, byte asc) get codes assigned
// sequentially with code = (prev_code + 1) << (cur_len - prev_len).
//
// To avoid full sort allocations, we iterate length values 1..A32_ESCAPE_LEN
// and within each length iterate byte values 0..255 in order. This implements
// the (length, byte) lexicographic sort implicitly in O(256 × max_len).

fn _canonical_codes(lens: array) -> array {
    let mut codes = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < 256 { codes.push(0); i = i + 1 }
    let mut code: i64 = 0
    let mut prev_len: i64 = 0
    let mut cur_len: i64 = 1
    while cur_len <= A32_MAX_CODE_LEN {
        let mut sym: i64 = 0
        while sym < 256 {
            if lens[sym] == cur_len {
                if prev_len == 0 {
                    code = 0
                } else {
                    code = (code + 1)
                    let shift: i64 = cur_len - prev_len
                    let mut s: i64 = 0
                    while s < shift { code = code * 2; s = s + 1 }
                }
                codes[sym] = code
                prev_len = cur_len
            }
            sym = sym + 1
        }
        cur_len = cur_len + 1
    }
    return codes
}

// ───────────────── class dispatcher ─────────────────

fn _class_table(class_id: int) -> array {
    if class_id == A32_CLASS_JSON { return _len_table_json() }
    if class_id == A32_CLASS_KOREAN { return _len_table_korean() }
    if class_id == A32_CLASS_SMALLFILE { return _len_table_smallfile() }
    return _len_table_text()
}

fn a32_v2_classify(buf: string) -> int {
    // v2 classifier — recovery vector E. SMALLFILE class subsumes JSON+text+
    // identifier mixed content typical of small files (89-498 B). Korean
    // detection preserved.
    let n: i64 = len(buf)
    if n == 0 { return A32_CLASS_SMALLFILE }
    let mut korean_leads: i64 = 0
    let mut p: i64 = 0
    while p < n {
        let b: i64 = _ord_at(buf, p)
        if b >= 225 && b <= 239 { korean_leads = korean_leads + 1 }
        p = p + 1
    }
    let korean_pct: i64 = (korean_leads * 100) / n
    if korean_pct >= A32_KOREAN_THRESH_X100 { return A32_CLASS_KOREAN }
    return A32_CLASS_SMALLFILE
}

fn a32_classify(buf: string) -> int {
    let n: i64 = len(buf)
    if n == 0 { return A32_CLASS_TEXT }
    let mut json_markers: i64 = 0
    let mut korean_leads: i64 = 0
    let mut p: i64 = 0
    while p < n {
        let b: i64 = _ord_at(buf, p)
        if b == 123 || b == 125 || b == 58 || b == 44 || b == 34 { json_markers = json_markers + 1 }
        if b >= 225 && b <= 239 { korean_leads = korean_leads + 1 }
        p = p + 1
    }
    let json_pct: i64 = (json_markers * 100) / n
    let korean_pct: i64 = (korean_leads * 100) / n
    if korean_pct >= A32_KOREAN_THRESH_X100 { return A32_CLASS_KOREAN }
    if json_pct >= A32_JSON_THRESH_X100 { return A32_CLASS_JSON }
    return A32_CLASS_TEXT
}

// ───────────────── PASS 3: bit-level encode/decode ─────────────────

// _bits_push: append the low `n_bits` of `value` to `bit_buf` MSB-first.
// `bit_buf` is an i64 array of bit values (0 or 1) for clarity / determinism.
fn _bits_push(bit_buf: array, value: int, n_bits: int) -> int {
    let mut k: i64 = n_bits - 1
    while k >= 0 {
        let div: i64 = 1
        let mut s: i64 = 0
        let mut acc: i64 = 1
        while s < k { acc = acc * 2; s = s + 1 }
        let bit: i64 = (value / acc) - (value / (acc * 2)) * 2
        bit_buf.push(bit)
        k = k - 1
    }
    return 0
}

// _bits_to_bytes: pack a bit array (MSB-first) into a byte array.
// Trailing bits in the last byte are zero-padded. The decoder uses the
// header's `n=` count + per-symbol Huffman lengths to know when to stop
// (no explicit stop symbol needed for static Huffman with known input length).
fn _bits_to_bytes(bits: array) -> array {
    let nb: i64 = len(bits)
    let mut out = []
    let mut i: i64 = 0
    while i < nb {
        let mut byte_val: i64 = 0
        let mut k: i64 = 0
        while k < 8 {
            byte_val = byte_val * 2
            if i + k < nb { byte_val = byte_val + bits[i + k] }
            k = k + 1
        }
        out.push(byte_val)
        i = i + 8
    }
    return out
}

// _bytes_to_bits: inverse of _bits_to_bytes. Returns array of 0/1 ints
// MSB-first within each byte.
fn _bytes_to_bits(bytes: array) -> array {
    let n: i64 = len(bytes)
    let mut out = []
    let mut i: i64 = 0
    while i < n {
        let b: i64 = bytes[i]
        let mut acc: i64 = 128
        let mut v: i64 = b
        let mut k: i64 = 0
        while k < 8 {
            let bit: i64 = if v >= acc { 1 } else { 0 }
            if v >= acc { v = v - acc }
            out.push(bit)
            acc = acc / 2
            k = k + 1
        }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

// ───────────────── base64url helpers (mirror A23/A18) ─────────────────

fn _b64_enc_bytes(bytes: array) -> string {
    let mut out = []
    let n: i64 = len(bytes)
    let mut i: i64 = 0
    while i < n {
        let b0: i64 = bytes[i]
        let b1: i64 = if i + 1 < n { bytes[i + 1] } else { 0 }
        let b2: i64 = if i + 2 < n { bytes[i + 2] } else { 0 }
        let acc: i64 = b0 * 65536 + b1 * 256 + b2
        let c0: i64 = acc / 262144
        let r0: i64 = acc - c0 * 262144
        let c1: i64 = r0 / 4096
        let r1: i64 = r0 - c1 * 4096
        let c2: i64 = r1 / 64
        let c3: i64 = r1 - c2 * 64
        let group: i64 = if i + 3 <= n { 4 } else { (n - i) + 1 }
        let chs = [c0, c1, c2, c3]
        let mut e: i64 = 0
        while e < group { out.push(A32_B64_ALPHA.substring(chs[e], chs[e] + 1)); e = e + 1 }
        i = i + 3
    }
    // Trailer: 4-char little-endian byte count (max 24 bits = 16777215).
    let mut nv: i64 = n
    if nv > 16777215 { nv = 16777215 }
    let t0: i64 = nv / 262144
    let r0t: i64 = nv - t0 * 262144
    let t1: i64 = r0t / 4096
    let r1t: i64 = r0t - t1 * 4096
    let t2: i64 = r1t / 64
    let t3: i64 = r1t - t2 * 64
    out.push(A32_B64_ALPHA.substring(t0, t0 + 1))
    out.push(A32_B64_ALPHA.substring(t1, t1 + 1))
    out.push(A32_B64_ALPHA.substring(t2, t2 + 1))
    out.push(A32_B64_ALPHA.substring(t3, t3 + 1))
    return out.join("")
}

fn _b64_char_idx(c: string) -> i64 { return A32_B64_ALPHA.index_of(c) }

// ───────────────── base94 helpers (v2 — recovery vector B, raw 157) ─────────────────
//
// base94 alphabet = printable ASCII 0x21..0x7E (94 chars). Packs 4 raw bytes
// (32 bits) → 5 base94 chars. Saving vs base64url 4/3: 5/4 = 1.25 → ~6pp wire
// reduction. Newline (0x0A) excluded → safe sigil-line wire.
fn _b94_enc_bytes(bytes: array) -> string {
    let mut out = []
    let n: i64 = len(bytes)
    let mut i: i64 = 0
    while i < n {
        let b0: i64 = bytes[i]
        let b1: i64 = if i + 1 < n { bytes[i + 1] } else { 0 }
        let b2: i64 = if i + 2 < n { bytes[i + 2] } else { 0 }
        let b3: i64 = if i + 3 < n { bytes[i + 3] } else { 0 }
        let hi: i64 = b0 * 256 + b1
        let lo: i64 = b2 * 256 + b3
        let acc: i64 = hi * 65536 + lo
        let p4: i64 = 94 * 94 * 94 * 94    // 78074896
        let p3: i64 = 94 * 94 * 94         // 830584
        let p2: i64 = 94 * 94              // 8836
        let p1: i64 = 94
        let d0: i64 = acc / p4
        let r0: i64 = acc - d0 * p4
        let d1: i64 = r0 / p3
        let r1: i64 = r0 - d1 * p3
        let d2: i64 = r1 / p2
        let r2: i64 = r1 - d2 * p2
        let d3: i64 = r2 / p1
        let d4: i64 = r2 - d3 * p1
        out.push(A32_B94_ALPHA.substring(d0, d0 + 1))
        out.push(A32_B94_ALPHA.substring(d1, d1 + 1))
        out.push(A32_B94_ALPHA.substring(d2, d2 + 1))
        out.push(A32_B94_ALPHA.substring(d3, d3 + 1))
        out.push(A32_B94_ALPHA.substring(d4, d4 + 1))
        i = i + 4
    }
    return out.join("")
}

fn _b94_char_idx(c: string) -> i64 { return A32_B94_ALPHA.index_of(c) }

fn _b94_dec_bytes(s: string, n_payload_bytes: int) -> array {
    let total: i64 = len(s)
    let mut out = []
    let mut i: i64 = 0
    while i + 5 <= total {
        let d0: i64 = _b94_char_idx(s.substring(i, i + 1))
        let d1: i64 = _b94_char_idx(s.substring(i + 1, i + 2))
        let d2: i64 = _b94_char_idx(s.substring(i + 2, i + 3))
        let d3: i64 = _b94_char_idx(s.substring(i + 3, i + 4))
        let d4: i64 = _b94_char_idx(s.substring(i + 4, i + 5))
        let p4: i64 = 94 * 94 * 94 * 94
        let p3: i64 = 94 * 94 * 94
        let p2: i64 = 94 * 94
        let p1: i64 = 94
        let acc: i64 = d0 * p4 + d1 * p3 + d2 * p2 + d3 * p1 + d4
        let hi: i64 = acc / 65536
        let lo: i64 = acc - hi * 65536
        let b0: i64 = hi / 256
        let b1: i64 = hi - b0 * 256
        let b2: i64 = lo / 256
        let b3: i64 = lo - b2 * 256
        out.push(b0)
        out.push(b1)
        out.push(b2)
        out.push(b3)
        i = i + 5
    }
    let mut final_out = []
    let mut fi: i64 = 0
    while fi < n_payload_bytes && fi < len(out) { final_out.push(out[fi]); fi = fi + 1 }
    return final_out
}

// 4-char base94 unsigned integer codec (range [0, 94^4-1] = [0, 78074895]).
fn _b94_enc_uint4(v: int) -> string {
    let mut x: i64 = v
    if x < 0 { x = 0 }
    let p3: i64 = 94 * 94 * 94
    let p2: i64 = 94 * 94
    let p1: i64 = 94
    let d0: i64 = x / p3
    let r0: i64 = x - d0 * p3
    let d1: i64 = r0 / p2
    let r1: i64 = r0 - d1 * p2
    let d2: i64 = r1 / p1
    let d3: i64 = r1 - d2 * p1
    let mut out = []
    out.push(A32_B94_ALPHA.substring(d0, d0 + 1))
    out.push(A32_B94_ALPHA.substring(d1, d1 + 1))
    out.push(A32_B94_ALPHA.substring(d2, d2 + 1))
    out.push(A32_B94_ALPHA.substring(d3, d3 + 1))
    return out.join("")
}

fn _b94_dec_uint4(s: string) -> i64 {
    if len(s) < 4 { return 0 }
    let d0: i64 = _b94_char_idx(s.substring(0, 1))
    let d1: i64 = _b94_char_idx(s.substring(1, 2))
    let d2: i64 = _b94_char_idx(s.substring(2, 3))
    let d3: i64 = _b94_char_idx(s.substring(3, 4))
    return d0 * 94 * 94 * 94 + d1 * 94 * 94 + d2 * 94 + d3
}

fn _b64_dec_bytes(s: string) -> array {
    let total: i64 = len(s)
    if total < 4 { return [] }
    let t0: i64 = _b64_char_idx(s.substring(total - 4, total - 3))
    let t1: i64 = _b64_char_idx(s.substring(total - 3, total - 2))
    let t2: i64 = _b64_char_idx(s.substring(total - 2, total - 1))
    let t3: i64 = _b64_char_idx(s.substring(total - 1, total))
    let bcount: i64 = t0 * 262144 + t1 * 4096 + t2 * 64 + t3
    let body_len: i64 = total - 4
    let mut out = []
    let mut i: i64 = 0
    while i < body_len {
        let group: i64 = if i + 4 <= body_len { 4 } else { body_len - i }
        let mut acc: i64 = 0
        let mut j: i64 = 0
        while j < 4 {
            let d: i64 = if j < group { _b64_char_idx(s.substring(i + j, i + j + 1)) } else { 0 }
            acc = acc * 64 + d
            j = j + 1
        }
        let by0: i64 = acc / 65536
        let rem: i64 = acc - by0 * 65536
        let by1: i64 = rem / 256
        let by2: i64 = rem - by1 * 256
        let bg: i64 = if group == 4 { 3 } else { group - 1 }
        if bg >= 1 { out.push(by0) }
        if bg >= 2 { out.push(by1) }
        if bg >= 3 { out.push(by2) }
        i = i + 4
    }
    let mut final_out = []
    let mut fi: i64 = 0
    while fi < bcount && fi < len(out) { final_out.push(out[fi]); fi = fi + 1 }
    return final_out
}

// ───────────────── encode wire ─────────────────
//
// _a32_encode_force: emit a32 wire regardless of saving (used by selftest +
// --force CLI). a32_encode wraps with raw 142 D2 try-and-revert: returns
// shortest of {a32-wire, identity}.

fn _a32_encode_force(text: string) -> string {
    let n: i64 = len(text)
    // Reject re-encoding (raw 65 idempotent: detect already-encoded prefix).
    if n >= 8 && text.substring(0, 8) == "# a32:s1" { return text }
    let class_id: i64 = a32_classify(text)
    let lens = _class_table(class_id)
    let codes = _canonical_codes(lens)
    let mut bits = []
    let mut p: i64 = 0
    while p < n {
        let sym: i64 = _ord_at(text, p)
        let l: i64 = lens[sym]
        // raw 91 honest C3: every byte has a canonical Huffman code (full
        // 256-byte coverage by class tables); no escape path needed.
        let _e3 = _bits_push(bits, codes[sym], l)
        p = p + 1
    }
    let payload_bytes = _bits_to_bytes(bits)
    let payload_b64 = _b64_enc_bytes(payload_bytes)
    let header = A32_HEADER_PREFIX + " n=" + to_string(n) + " c=" + to_string(class_id)
    let body = A32_SIGIL + payload_b64
    return header + "\n" + body + "\n"
}

// a32_encode: try-and-revert (raw 142 D2) + small-file gate (raw 156).
fn a32_encode(text: string) -> string {
    let n: i64 = len(text)
    if n < A32_MIN_BYTES { return text }
    if n > A32_SMALL_FILE_BOUND { return text }
    if n >= 8 && text.substring(0, 8) == "# a32:s1" { return text }
    if n >= 3 && text.substring(0, 3) == A32_V2_HEADER_TAG { return text }
    let enc = _a32_encode_force(text)
    if len(enc) < n { return enc }
    return text
}

// ───────────────── v2 encode wire (recovery vectors B+C+D+E) ─────────────────
// Wire: ^c2<C><LLLL><PPPP><base94-body>\n
//   ^c2  3 bytes — sigil + version
//   <C>  1 byte  — class digit '0'..'3'
//   <LLLL> 4 bytes — base94 raw input length
//   <PPPP> 4 bytes — base94 payload byte count
//   body — base94 5/4 from Huffman bit-packed payload
//   \n   trailer
// Total fixed overhead: 12 bytes + 1 newline = 13 bytes (vs v1 ~37 bytes).
fn _a32_v2_encode_force(text: string) -> string {
    let n: i64 = len(text)
    if n >= 3 && text.substring(0, 3) == A32_V2_HEADER_TAG { return text }
    if n >= 8 && text.substring(0, 8) == "# a32:s1" { return text }
    let class_id: i64 = a32_v2_classify(text)
    let lens = _class_table(class_id)
    let codes = _canonical_codes(lens)
    let mut bits = []
    let mut p: i64 = 0
    while p < n {
        let sym: i64 = _ord_at(text, p)
        let l: i64 = lens[sym]
        let _e3 = _bits_push(bits, codes[sym], l)
        p = p + 1
    }
    let payload_bytes = _bits_to_bytes(bits)
    let payload_b94 = _b94_enc_bytes(payload_bytes)
    let class_digit = chr(48 + class_id)
    let len_field = _b94_enc_uint4(n)
    let payload_b_count = len(payload_bytes)
    let payload_field = _b94_enc_uint4(payload_b_count)
    return A32_V2_HEADER_TAG + class_digit + len_field + payload_field + payload_b94 + "\n"
}

// a32_v2_encode: raw 142 D2 try-and-revert. Picks shortest of {v2, v1, identity}.
fn a32_v2_encode(text: string) -> string {
    let n: i64 = len(text)
    if n < A32_V2_MIN_BYTES { return text }
    if n > A32_SMALL_FILE_BOUND { return text }
    if n >= 3 && text.substring(0, 3) == A32_V2_HEADER_TAG { return text }
    if n >= 8 && text.substring(0, 8) == "# a32:s1" { return text }
    let enc_v2 = _a32_v2_encode_force(text)
    let enc_v1 = _a32_encode_force(text)
    let v2_len: i64 = len(enc_v2)
    let v1_len: i64 = len(enc_v1)
    let mut best_len: i64 = n
    let mut best: string = text
    if v2_len < best_len { best_len = v2_len; best = enc_v2 }
    if v1_len < best_len { best_len = v1_len; best = enc_v1 }
    return best
}

// ───────────────── decode wire ─────────────────

// _decode_walk: walk the bit stream symbol-by-symbol using the canonical
// codebook. We scan lengths 1..A32_ESCAPE_LEN, accumulating bits until the
// running prefix matches a code at the current length. On match, emit the
// corresponding symbol; on length=A32_ESCAPE_LEN exact-match A32_ESCAPE_CODE,
// emit an escape (read next 8 bits as raw symbol byte). Decoded output stops
// when n_bytes symbols have been emitted (per header).

fn _decode_walk(bits: array, codes: array, lens: array, n_bytes: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let nb: i64 = len(bits)
    let mut bi: i64 = 0
    let mut emitted: i64 = 0
    while emitted < n_bytes && bi < nb {
        let mut prefix: i64 = 0
        let mut clen: i64 = 0
        let mut found: bool = false
        let mut found_sym: i64 = 0
        while !found && clen < A32_MAX_CODE_LEN {
            if bi >= nb { break }
            prefix = prefix * 2 + bits[bi]
            bi = bi + 1
            clen = clen + 1
            // Linear scan over 256 symbols; class tables guarantee any valid
            // bit prefix matches at most one symbol at the current length
            // (canonical Huffman prefix property).
            let mut sym: i64 = 0
            while sym < 256 {
                if lens[sym] == clen && codes[sym] == prefix {
                    found = true
                    found_sym = sym
                    break
                }
                sym = sym + 1
            }
        }
        if !found { break }
        out.push(found_sym)
        emitted = emitted + 1
    }
    return out
}

fn _a32_decode_to_bytes(stream: string) -> array {
    let lines = stream.split("\n")
    if len(lines) < 2 { return [] }
    let header = lines[0]
    if len(header) < 8 || header.substring(0, 8) != "# a32:s1" { return [] }
    let n_pos: i64 = header.index_of(" n=")
    if n_pos < 0 { return [] }
    let c_pos: i64 = header.index_of(" c=")
    let n_end: i64 = if c_pos > n_pos { c_pos } else { len(header) }
    let n_bytes: i64 = parse_int(header.substring(n_pos + 3, n_end))
    let class_id: i64 = if c_pos > 0 {
        parse_int(header.substring(c_pos + 3, len(header)))
    } else {
        A32_CLASS_TEXT
    }
    let mut body_b64 = ""
    let mut i = 1
    while i < len(lines) {
        let l = lines[i]
        if len(l) >= 2 && l.substring(0, 2) == A32_SIGIL {
            body_b64 = l.substring(2, len(l))
            break
        }
        i = i + 1
    }
    if len(body_b64) == 0 { return [] }
    let payload_bytes = _b64_dec_bytes(body_b64)
    let bits = _bytes_to_bits(payload_bytes)
    let lens = _class_table(class_id)
    let codes = _canonical_codes(lens)
    return _decode_walk(bits, codes, lens, n_bytes)
}

fn a32_decode(stream: string) -> string {
    let lines = stream.split("\n")
    if len(lines) < 2 { return stream }
    let header = lines[0]
    if len(header) < 8 || header.substring(0, 8) != "# a32:s1" { return stream }
    let bytes = _a32_decode_to_bytes(stream)
    if len(bytes) == 0 { return stream }
    let mut parts = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < len(bytes) { parts.push(chr(bytes[i])); i = i + 1 }
    return parts.join("")
}

// ───────────────── v2 decode wire ─────────────────
fn _a32_v2_decode_to_bytes(stream: string) -> array {
    let total: i64 = len(stream)
    if total < 12 { return [] }
    if stream.substring(0, 3) != A32_V2_HEADER_TAG { return [] }
    let class_ch: string = stream.substring(3, 4)
    let class_id: i64 = ord(class_ch) - 48
    if class_id < 0 || class_id > 3 { return [] }
    let len_field: string = stream.substring(4, 8)
    let n_bytes: i64 = _b94_dec_uint4(len_field)
    let payload_field: string = stream.substring(8, 12)
    let payload_b_count: i64 = _b94_dec_uint4(payload_field)
    let mut body_end: i64 = total
    if total >= 1 && stream.substring(total - 1, total) == "\n" { body_end = total - 1 }
    let body: string = stream.substring(12, body_end)
    let payload_bytes = _b94_dec_bytes(body, payload_b_count)
    let bits = _bytes_to_bits(payload_bytes)
    let lens = _class_table(class_id)
    let codes = _canonical_codes(lens)
    return _decode_walk(bits, codes, lens, n_bytes)
}

fn a32_v2_decode(stream: string) -> string {
    let n: i64 = len(stream)
    if n < 3 || stream.substring(0, 3) != A32_V2_HEADER_TAG { return stream }
    let bytes = _a32_v2_decode_to_bytes(stream)
    if len(bytes) == 0 { return stream }
    let mut parts = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < len(bytes) { parts.push(chr(bytes[i])); i = i + 1 }
    return parts.join("")
}

fn a32_decode_any(stream: string) -> string {
    let n: i64 = len(stream)
    if n >= 3 && stream.substring(0, 3) == A32_V2_HEADER_TAG { return a32_v2_decode(stream) }
    if n >= 8 && stream.substring(0, 8) == "# a32:s1" { return a32_decode(stream) }
    return stream
}

// ───────────────── selftest (5 fixtures) ─────────────────

fn _selftest() -> int {
    println("# hxc_a32_static_huffman selftest (FIRST TICK BUILD — PASS 1+2+3 + 5 fixtures)")
    let mut pass = 0
    let mut fail = 0

    // ─── Fixture 1: small JSON (text-heavy with structural markers) ───
    //   Falsifier on round-trip fail: F-A32-3 (raw 65/68).
    //   Class detection: JSON markers > 8% → A32_CLASS_JSON.
    let json_small = "{\"ts\":\"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z\",\"ev\":\"first_tick\",\"saving\":0.97}\n{\"ts\":\"2026-04-28T00:01:00Z\",\"ev\":\"first_tick\",\"saving\":0.97}\n"
    let class1 = a32_classify(json_small)
    let enc1 = _a32_encode_force(json_small)
    let dec1 = a32_decode(enc1)
    if dec1 == json_small && class1 == A32_CLASS_JSON {
        let s1 = ((len(json_small) - len(enc1)) * 100) / len(json_small)
        pass = pass + 1
        println("  PASS: fixture-1 small JSON byte-eq class=" + to_string(class1)
                + " " + to_string(len(json_small)) + " -> " + to_string(len(enc1))
                + " (" + to_string(s1) + "% saving)")
    } else {
        fail = fail + 1
        println("  FAIL: fixture-1 small JSON round-trip lost (class=" + to_string(class1)
                + ", expected " + to_string(A32_CLASS_JSON) + "), orig_len="
                + to_string(len(json_small)) + " got_len=" + to_string(len(dec1))
                + " → F-A32-3 TRIPPED")
    }

    // ─── Fixture 2: small text (English prose, < 2KB) ───
    //   Class detection: text-heavy default.
    let phrase = "the quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog "
    let mut text_small = ""
    let mut k2 = 0
    while k2 < 8 { text_small = text_small + phrase; k2 = k2 + 1 }
    let class2 = a32_classify(text_small)
    let enc2 = _a32_encode_force(text_small)
    let dec2 = a32_decode(enc2)
    if dec2 == text_small && class2 == A32_CLASS_TEXT {
        let s2 = ((len(text_small) - len(enc2)) * 100) / len(text_small)
        pass = pass + 1
        println("  PASS: fixture-2 small text byte-eq class=" + to_string(class2)
                + " " + to_string(len(text_small)) + " -> " + to_string(len(enc2))
                + " (" + to_string(s2) + "% saving)")
    } else {
        fail = fail + 1
        println("  FAIL: fixture-2 small text round-trip lost (class=" + to_string(class2)
                + ", expected " + to_string(A32_CLASS_TEXT) + "), orig_len="
                + to_string(len(text_small)) + " got_len=" + to_string(len(dec2))
                + " → F-A32-3 TRIPPED")
    }

    // ─── Fixture 3: Korean tag (UTF-8 multibyte) ───
    //   Class detection: UTF-8 lead bytes E1..EF > 5% → A32_CLASS_KOREAN.
    //   Round-trip MUST be byte-identical at byte-array level (not string —
    //   .substring(i, i+1) on multibyte UTF-8 in hexa returns the byte, not
    //   the codepoint, so byte-array comparison is the correct invariant).
    let kor_phrase = "안녕 세계 — 정적 허프만 A32 작은-파일 클래스. raw 9 hexa 자기-호스트. "
    let mut buf_kor = ""
    let mut k3 = 0
    while k3 < 6 { buf_kor = buf_kor + kor_phrase; k3 = k3 + 1 }
    let class3 = a32_classify(buf_kor)
    let enc3 = _a32_encode_force(buf_kor)
    let dec3_bytes = _a32_decode_to_bytes(enc3)
    let mut ok3 = true
    let nk: i64 = len(buf_kor)
    if len(dec3_bytes) != nk { ok3 = false }
    let mut q3: i64 = 0
    while ok3 && q3 < nk {
        if dec3_bytes[q3] != _ord_at(buf_kor, q3) { ok3 = false }
        q3 = q3 + 1
    }
    if ok3 && class3 == A32_CLASS_KOREAN {
        let s3: i64 = ((nk - len(enc3)) * 100) / nk
        pass = pass + 1
        println("  PASS: fixture-3 Korean multibyte byte-array byte-eq class="
                + to_string(class3) + " " + to_string(nk) + " -> "
                + to_string(len(enc3)) + " (" + to_string(s3) + "% saving)")
    } else {
        fail = fail + 1
        println("  FAIL: fixture-3 Korean round-trip (class=" + to_string(class3)
                + ", expected " + to_string(A32_CLASS_KOREAN)
                + ", orig_len=" + to_string(nk) + ", got_len=" + to_string(len(dec3_bytes))
                + ") → F-A32-3 TRIPPED")
    }

    // ─── Fixture 4: mixed micro (small mixed-content < 256 bytes) ───
    //   Tests escape path: ASCII bytes outside the class table fall to escape.
    let micro = "id=42; name=\"Alice\"; status=ACTIVE; ratio=0.875\nid=43; name=\"Bob\"; status=PENDING; ratio=0.5\n"
    let class4 = a32_classify(micro)
    let enc4 = _a32_encode_force(micro)
    let dec4 = a32_decode(enc4)
    if dec4 == micro {
        let s4 = ((len(micro) - len(enc4)) * 100) / len(micro)
        pass = pass + 1
        println("  PASS: fixture-4 mixed micro byte-eq class=" + to_string(class4)
                + " " + to_string(len(micro)) + " -> " + to_string(len(enc4))
                + " (" + to_string(s4) + "% saving)")
    } else {
        fail = fail + 1
        println("  FAIL: fixture-4 mixed micro round-trip lost orig_len="
                + to_string(len(micro)) + " got_len=" + to_string(len(dec4))
                + " → F-A32-3 TRIPPED")
    }

    // ─── Fixture 5: passthrough idempotent (raw 65 + 68) ───
    //   Below MIN_BYTES → identity. Re-encode also identity.
    let tiny = "abc123"
    let enc5 = a32_encode(tiny)
    let enc5b = a32_encode(enc5)
    if enc5 == tiny && enc5b == tiny {
        pass = pass + 1
        println("  PASS: fixture-5 short-input passthrough idempotent (raw 65 + 68)")
    } else {
        fail = fail + 1
        println("  FAIL: fixture-5 short-input idempotency broken")
    }

    // Bonus assertion: canonical Huffman codebook is well-formed for all 3
    // class tables — no two distinct symbols share the same (length, code)
    // pair, AND the Kraft inequality Σ 2^(MAX_LEN-L_i) ≤ 2^MAX_LEN holds
    // (otherwise the implicit Huffman tree would be invalid and the encoded
    // bitstream non-prefix-free).
    let class_names = ["text", "json", "korean"]
    let mut cls_id = 0
    while cls_id < 3 {
        let lens_c = _class_table(cls_id)
        let codes_c = _canonical_codes(lens_c)
        let mut codebook_ok = true
        let mut a = 0
        while codebook_ok && a < 256 {
            if lens_c[a] > 0 {
                let mut b = a + 1
                while codebook_ok && b < 256 {
                    if lens_c[b] == lens_c[a] && codes_c[b] == codes_c[a] { codebook_ok = false }
                    b = b + 1
                }
            }
            a = a + 1
        }
        // Kraft sum: count each symbol as 2^(MAX_LEN - lens[i]), assert ≤ 2^MAX_LEN.
        let mut kraft_sum: i64 = 0
        let kraft_cap: i64 = 4096    // 2^12
        let mut s2: i64 = 0
        while s2 < 256 {
            let l: i64 = lens_c[s2]
            if l > 0 && l <= A32_MAX_CODE_LEN {
                let mut weight: i64 = 1
                let mut e: i64 = 0
                let target: i64 = A32_MAX_CODE_LEN - l
                while e < target { weight = weight * 2; e = e + 1 }
                kraft_sum = kraft_sum + weight
            }
            s2 = s2 + 1
        }
        let kraft_ok: bool = (kraft_sum <= kraft_cap)
        if codebook_ok && kraft_ok {
            println("  NOTE: " + class_names[cls_id] + " codebook well-formed (kraft="
                    + to_string(kraft_sum) + "/" + to_string(kraft_cap) + ")")
        } else {
            fail = fail + 1
            println("  FAIL: " + class_names[cls_id] + " codebook DEGENERATE codebook_ok="
                    + to_string(codebook_ok) + " kraft_ok=" + to_string(kraft_ok)
                    + " sum=" + to_string(kraft_sum) + " → F-A32-3 INTERNAL TRIPPED")
        }
        cls_id = cls_id + 1
    }

    // ───────────── v2 selftest fixtures (recovery vectors B+C+D+E) ─────────────
    // ─── Fixture 6 (v2-1): JSON small ───
    let class_v2_1 = a32_v2_classify(json_small)
    let enc_v2_1 = _a32_v2_encode_force(json_small)
    let dec_v2_1 = a32_v2_decode(enc_v2_1)
    if dec_v2_1 == json_small {
        let sv2_1 = ((len(json_small) - len(enc_v2_1)) * 100) / len(json_small)
        pass = pass + 1
        println("  PASS: fixture-6 v2 JSON byte-eq class=" + to_string(class_v2_1)
                + " " + to_string(len(json_small)) + " -> " + to_string(len(enc_v2_1))
                + " (" + to_string(sv2_1) + "% saving)")
    } else {
        fail = fail + 1
        println("  FAIL: fixture-6 v2 JSON round-trip lost orig_len="
                + to_string(len(json_small)) + " got_len=" + to_string(len(dec_v2_1))
                + " → F-A32-3-v2 TRIPPED")
    }

    // ─── Fixture 7 (v2-2): small text ───
    let enc_v2_2 = _a32_v2_encode_force(text_small)
    let dec_v2_2 = a32_v2_decode(enc_v2_2)
    if dec_v2_2 == text_small {
        let sv2_2 = ((len(text_small) - len(enc_v2_2)) * 100) / len(text_small)
        pass = pass + 1
        println("  PASS: fixture-7 v2 text byte-eq "
                + to_string(len(text_small)) + " -> " + to_string(len(enc_v2_2))
                + " (" + to_string(sv2_2) + "% saving)")
    } else {
        fail = fail + 1
        println("  FAIL: fixture-7 v2 text round-trip lost orig_len="
                + to_string(len(text_small)) + " got_len=" + to_string(len(dec_v2_2)))
    }

    // ─── Fixture 8 (v2-3): Korean multibyte ───
    let class_v2_3 = a32_v2_classify(buf_kor)
    let enc_v2_3 = _a32_v2_encode_force(buf_kor)
    let dec_v2_3_bytes = _a32_v2_decode_to_bytes(enc_v2_3)
    let mut ok_v2_3 = true
    let nk_v2: i64 = len(buf_kor)
    if len(dec_v2_3_bytes) != nk_v2 { ok_v2_3 = false }
    let mut q_v2_3: i64 = 0
    while ok_v2_3 && q_v2_3 < nk_v2 {
        if dec_v2_3_bytes[q_v2_3] != _ord_at(buf_kor, q_v2_3) { ok_v2_3 = false }
        q_v2_3 = q_v2_3 + 1
    }
    if ok_v2_3 && class_v2_3 == A32_CLASS_KOREAN {
        let sv2_3: i64 = ((nk_v2 - len(enc_v2_3)) * 100) / nk_v2
        pass = pass + 1
        println("  PASS: fixture-8 v2 Korean byte-array byte-eq class="
                + to_string(class_v2_3) + " " + to_string(nk_v2) + " -> "
                + to_string(len(enc_v2_3)) + " (" + to_string(sv2_3) + "% saving)")
    } else {
        fail = fail + 1
        println("  FAIL: fixture-8 v2 Korean round-trip class=" + to_string(class_v2_3)
                + " orig_len=" + to_string(nk_v2) + " got_len=" + to_string(len(dec_v2_3_bytes)))
    }

    // ─── Fixture 9 (v2-4): mixed-micro larger sample (≥512 to test V2_MIN_BYTES) ───
    let micro_phrase = "id=42; name=\"Alice\"; status=ACTIVE; ratio=0.875; tag=foo_bar; key=\"value-1\";\n"
    let mut micro_big = ""
    let mut k_mb = 0
    while k_mb < 8 { micro_big = micro_big + micro_phrase; k_mb = k_mb + 1 }
    let class_v2_4 = a32_v2_classify(micro_big)
    let enc_v2_4 = _a32_v2_encode_force(micro_big)
    let dec_v2_4 = a32_v2_decode(enc_v2_4)
    if dec_v2_4 == micro_big {
        let sv2_4 = ((len(micro_big) - len(enc_v2_4)) * 100) / len(micro_big)
        pass = pass + 1
        println("  PASS: fixture-9 v2 mixed-micro byte-eq class=" + to_string(class_v2_4)
                + " " + to_string(len(micro_big)) + " -> " + to_string(len(enc_v2_4))
                + " (" + to_string(sv2_4) + "% saving)")
    } else {
        fail = fail + 1
        println("  FAIL: fixture-9 v2 mixed-micro round-trip lost orig_len="
                + to_string(len(micro_big)) + " got_len=" + to_string(len(dec_v2_4)))
    }

    // ─── Fixture 10 (v2-5): v2 sub-MIN_BYTES passthrough idempotent ───
    let small_300 = "abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789 "
    let mut ten_x = ""
    let mut k_idx = 0
    while k_idx < 7 { ten_x = ten_x + small_300; k_idx = k_idx + 1 }
    let enc_v2_5a = a32_v2_encode(ten_x)
    let enc_v2_5b = a32_v2_encode(enc_v2_5a)
    if enc_v2_5a == ten_x && enc_v2_5b == ten_x {
        pass = pass + 1
        println("  PASS: fixture-10 v2 sub-MIN_BYTES passthrough idempotent ("
                + to_string(len(ten_x)) + "B < " + to_string(A32_V2_MIN_BYTES) + "B floor)")
    } else {
        fail = fail + 1
        println("  FAIL: fixture-10 v2 idempotency broken")
    }

    // Codebook sanity for SMALLFILE class.
    let lens_sf = _class_table(A32_CLASS_SMALLFILE)
    let codes_sf = _canonical_codes(lens_sf)
    let mut sf_ok = true
    let mut sa = 0
    while sf_ok && sa < 256 {
        if lens_sf[sa] > 0 {
            let mut sb = sa + 1
            while sf_ok && sb < 256 {
                if lens_sf[sb] == lens_sf[sa] && codes_sf[sb] == codes_sf[sa] { sf_ok = false }
                sb = sb + 1
            }
        }
        sa = sa + 1
    }
    let mut kraft_sf: i64 = 0
    let mut sx: i64 = 0
    while sx < 256 {
        let l_sf: i64 = lens_sf[sx]
        if l_sf > 0 && l_sf <= A32_MAX_CODE_LEN {
            let mut weight_sf: i64 = 1
            let mut e_sf: i64 = 0
            let target_sf: i64 = A32_MAX_CODE_LEN - l_sf
            while e_sf < target_sf { weight_sf = weight_sf * 2; e_sf = e_sf + 1 }
            kraft_sf = kraft_sf + weight_sf
        }
        sx = sx + 1
    }
    let kraft_sf_ok: bool = (kraft_sf <= 4096)
    if sf_ok && kraft_sf_ok {
        println("  NOTE: smallfile codebook well-formed (kraft="
                + to_string(kraft_sf) + "/4096)")
    } else {
        fail = fail + 1
        println("  FAIL: smallfile codebook DEGENERATE codebook_ok="
                + to_string(sf_ok) + " kraft_ok=" + to_string(kraft_sf_ok)
                + " sum=" + to_string(kraft_sf) + " → F-A32-3 INTERNAL TRIPPED")
    }

    println("Results: " + to_string(pass) + " PASS / " + to_string(fail) + " FAIL")
    println("__HXC_A32_SELFTEST__ " + (if fail == 0 { "PASS" } else { "FAIL" })
            + " (v1 5 fixtures + v2 5 fixtures = 10/10; v2 recovery vectors B+C+D+E applied)")
    if fail == 0 { return 0 }
    return 1
}

// ───────────────── main CLI ─────────────────

fn main() {
    let av = argv()
    let mut has_selftest = false
    let mut has_encode = false
    let mut has_decode = false
    let mut has_force = false
    let mut has_v2 = false
    let mut k = 0
    while k < len(av) {
        if av[k] == "--selftest" { has_selftest = true }
        if av[k] == "encode" { has_encode = true }
        if av[k] == "decode" { has_decode = true }
        if av[k] == "--force" { has_force = true }
        if av[k] == "--v2" { has_v2 = true }
        k = k + 1
    }
    if has_selftest { exit(_selftest()) }
    if has_encode || has_decode {
        let mut sub_idx = 0
        let mut q = 0
        while q < len(av) {
            if av[q] == "encode" || av[q] == "decode" { sub_idx = q; break }
            q = q + 1
        }
        let mut paths = []
        let mut q2 = sub_idx + 1
        while q2 < len(av) {
            let a = av[q2]
            if len(a) >= 2 && a.substring(0, 2) == "--" { q2 = q2 + 1; continue }
            paths.push(a)
            q2 = q2 + 1
        }
        if len(paths) < 2 {
            eprintln("usage: hexa hxc_a32_static_huffman.hexa <encode|decode> [--v2] [--force] <in> <out>")
            exit(3)
        }
        let in_path = paths[0]
        let out_path = paths[1]
        if has_encode {
            let txt = read_file(in_path)
            let res = if has_v2 {
                if has_force { _a32_v2_encode_force(txt) } else { a32_v2_encode(txt) }
            } else {
                if has_force { _a32_encode_force(txt) } else { a32_encode(txt) }
            }
            let _w = write_file(out_path, res)
            let saving = if len(txt) > 0 { ((len(txt) - len(res)) * 100) / len(txt) } else { 0 }
            let class_id = if has_v2 { a32_v2_classify(txt) } else { a32_classify(txt) }
            let ver_tag = if has_v2 { "v2" } else { "v1" }
            println("a32 encode " + ver_tag + " class=" + to_string(class_id)
                    + " raw=" + to_string(len(txt))
                    + " enc=" + to_string(len(res)) + " saving=" + to_string(saving) + "%")
            exit(0)
        }
        let txt = read_file(in_path)
        let n = len(txt)
        let bytes = if n >= 3 && txt.substring(0, 3) == A32_V2_HEADER_TAG {
            _a32_v2_decode_to_bytes(txt)
        } else {
            _a32_decode_to_bytes(txt)
        }
        if len(bytes) == 0 {
            let _w = write_file(out_path, txt)
        } else {
            let _w = write_bytes(out_path, bytes)
        }
        exit(0)
    }
    eprintln("usage: hexa hxc_a32_static_huffman.hexa [--selftest | encode [--v2] [--force] <in> <out> | decode <in> <out>]")
    exit(3)
}
